    id: 'act-read-019',
    passage: `The word "plagiarism" entered English from the Latin plagiarius, meaning "kidnapper," a metaphor the Roman poet Martial used when he accused a rival of stealing his verses. The theft metaphor has structured debates about intellectual property ever since, though it has also been contested from multiple directions. Authors in oral traditions, where composition involves communal variation on shared material, have sometimes viewed Western copyright's possessive individualism as a foreign imposition. Postmodern critics like Roland Barthes declared authorship itself a myth, arguing in his 1967 essay "The Death of the Author" that a text's meaning arises from the reader and cultural context, not from any originating creative mind. Meanwhile, the digital age introduced large-scale text reuse at unprecedented speeds, forcing courts and scholars to revisit questions about where influence ends and theft begins. The kidnapper metaphor remains in common use — but it has never gone unquestioned.`,
