    id: 'act-read-030',
    passage: `The Cambrian Explosion — a period roughly 538 to 485 million years ago during which most major animal body plans appear in the fossil record — remains one of evolutionary biology's most debated events. Within a geologically brief window of approximately 20 million years, organisms with bilateral symmetry, hard shells, compound eyes, and segmented bodies appear with apparent suddenness. One influential explanation, the "developmental gene" hypothesis, proposes that the evolution of Hox genes — regulatory genes that control the body plan during embryonic development — enabled rapid morphological innovation by allowing a single genetic change to reorganize entire body structures. Alternative hypotheses cite environmental factors: rising oxygen levels in the oceans may have enabled the higher metabolic rates required for active predation, triggering an arms race of defensive and offensive adaptations. Most contemporary biologists regard the Cambrian Explosion as likely multicausal, resisting any single-factor explanation.`,
