    passage: `Urban heat islands form when natural land cover is replaced by dense concentrations of pavement, buildings, and other surfaces that absorb and re-emit the sun's heat more effectively than natural landscapes. In major metropolitan areas, summertime temperatures can be 1 to 7 degrees Celsius higher than in surrounding rural areas, a difference that intensifies heat waves and increases energy consumption for cooling. Low-income neighborhoods in many American cities are disproportionately affected because urban greenery — parks, street trees, green roofs — correlates strongly with property values and investment. Researchers at the University of Richmond found that formerly redlined neighborhoods are, on average, 2.6°C hotter today than those that received the highest investment grades in the 1930s. This physical effect of historical disinvestment creates a compounding burden: hotter neighborhoods require more air conditioning, increasing electricity bills for residents least able to absorb that cost.`,
