    passage: `The term "gig economy" describes a labor market characterized by short-term contracts and freelance work rather than permanent jobs. Proponents argue that gig arrangements offer workers unprecedented flexibility — the ability to set their own hours, choose clients, and work from anywhere. Critics counter that this flexibility is often illusory, pointing to studies showing that many gig workers are effectively full-time employees of platforms like Uber or DoorDash but without access to employer-sponsored health insurance, paid leave, unemployment insurance, or retirement contributions. A 2019 survey by the Economic Policy Institute found that app-based drivers worked an average of 43 hours per week — comparable to traditional full-time employment — but earned median hourly wages below the federal poverty threshold after vehicle expenses. The legal status of gig workers as "independent contractors" rather than employees remains contested in courts and legislatures across the United States and Europe.`,
