    id: 'act-read-037',
    passage: `The marshmallow test, conducted by psychologist Walter Mischel at Stanford in the late 1960s, became one of the most cited studies in developmental psychology. Children were offered a marshmallow and told they could eat it immediately or wait fifteen minutes to receive two marshmallows. Follow-up studies suggested children who waited showed better academic outcomes, higher SAT scores, and even lower body-mass indexes in adulthood. The study was popularized as evidence that willpower or "delay of gratification" was a stable, predictive trait. However, a 2018 replication study by researchers at New York University challenged these findings significantly. Using a larger and more economically diverse sample, the team found that after controlling for socioeconomic status and family environment, the predictive power of waiting time essentially disappeared. Children from lower-income households, who waited less often, may have been responding rationally to an environment where promised resources frequently failed to materialize.`,
