    id: 'act-read-041',
    passage: `Surrealism, the artistic and literary movement that emerged in Paris in the 1920s, drew heavily on Sigmund Freud's theories of the unconscious mind. The movement's founder, André Breton, defined surrealism in his 1924 Manifesto as "pure psychic automatism" — the attempt to express thought "in the absence of any control exercised by reason." Surrealist painters like Salvador Dalí and René Magritte juxtaposed logically incompatible images to create dreamlike canvases that unsettled rational categorization. Though the movement aligned itself with Marxist politics — seeing liberation from unconscious repression as parallel to liberation from capitalist social structures — this alliance was consistently uneasy. Breton expelled multiple members for insufficiently radical politics, and the Communist Party's insistence on socialist realism in art was fundamentally at odds with surrealism's embrace of irrationality. The movement's internal contradictions proved as defining as its innovations.`,
