    id: 'act-read-050',
    passage: `Antibiotic resistance — the capacity of bacteria to survive exposure to drugs designed to kill them — represents one of the most serious public health crises of the twenty-first century. Resistant bacteria emerge through natural selection: when a population is exposed to an antibiotic, susceptible individuals die while those with resistance mutations survive and reproduce. The crisis is accelerated by several human behaviors: overprescription in medicine, use of antibiotics as growth promoters in livestock, and patients failing to complete prescribed courses (leaving partially-resistant survivors). The World Health Organization estimates that by 2050, antimicrobial resistance could cause 10 million deaths annually — surpassing cancer — if no action is taken. Development of new antibiotics has slowed dramatically because the drugs are economically unattractive to pharmaceutical companies: a two-week antibiotic course generates less revenue than a lifetime medication for chronic disease. Several nations have proposed "push and pull" incentive models to address this market failure.`,
