    passage: `My grandfather kept a notebook of things he planned to do after the war. It was a small, water-stained thing he'd bought in a pharmacy in London in 1943, and he never threw it away, though by the time I knew him the notebook's list had become a private joke between us — almost every item had been completed, or abandoned, or rendered irrelevant by the decades between the writing and the reading. "Learn Portuguese" appeared twice, underlined. He never did. "Buy a motorboat" was crossed out with a single line; he had bought and promptly sold one in 1957, which he considered the crossing-out sufficient for. When I was twelve, he let me read the whole notebook, except for one page, which he had glued shut with the care of someone who had thought about it. I never asked about that page. I think now that the not-asking was its own kind of answer.`,
