    id: 'act-read-076',
    passage: `The city had been rebuilt so many times that its oldest residents argued about which version was authentic. The colonnade on the south plaza had burned in 1892, been rebuilt identically in 1910, burned again in 1961, and stood now in its third incarnation, using the same stone quarried from the same mountains but shaped by different hands in a different century. Tourists photographed it without knowing. Historians argued about whether it was, in any meaningful sense, the same colonnade. The philosopher Thomas Hobbes had asked a similar question about a ship repaired plank by plank until no original material remained — was it still the same ship? The city's colonnade sharpened the question further: the design was the same, the stone was the same, but not a single atom of the original structure survived. What was left, then, but an idea — and was an idea enough to make something real?`,
