    passage: `The ozone layer, a region of Earth's stratosphere approximately 15 to 35 kilometers above the surface, absorbs the majority of the sun's ultraviolet radiation — particularly the high-energy UV-B and UV-C wavelengths most damaging to biological systems. The discovery in 1985 that a massive "hole" — technically a severe thinning — had opened over Antarctica shocked the scientific community, which had been monitoring stratospheric ozone since the early 1970s. Subsequent research pinpointed the cause: chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs) used in aerosols, refrigerants, and foam packaging break down in the stratosphere when exposed to UV light, releasing chlorine atoms that catalytically destroy ozone molecules. The Montreal Protocol of 1987, signed by virtually every nation on Earth, phased out CFC production. By 2020, the ozone layer had recovered to levels not seen since the 1970s — one of the most successful examples of international environmental cooperation in history.`,
