    id: 'act-read-094',
    passage: `The economics of attention — the study of how producers compete for human notice in an information-saturated environment — has become central to digital platform design. Psychologist B.J. Fogg's "captology" framework analyzed how technology is designed to influence behavior through carefully engineered triggers, motivations, and ability cues. Variable reward schedules — the same mechanism that makes slot machines compelling — lie at the heart of social media notifications: the unpredictability of "likes" and comments creates a stronger habituating effect than predictable rewards would. Former tech industry insiders, including early Facebook president Sean Parker, have publicly described the platforms as deliberately engineered to exploit psychological vulnerabilities. Proponents of these platforms argue they enable genuine human connection and that adults should bear responsibility for managing their own screen time. Critics counter that designing systems to exploit cognitive biases without disclosure raises ethical questions analogous to those surrounding subliminal advertising, which is banned in many countries.`,
