    id: 'act-read-098',
    passage: `The theory of plate tectonics, now the foundational framework of geology, was not widely accepted until the 1960s — despite accumulating evidence dating back to Alfred Wegener's 1912 proposal that the continents had once been joined in a supercontinent he called Pangaea. Wegener's evidence was largely observational: the complementary shapes of South America and Africa, matching fossil records across what are now separate continents, and similar rock formations on different sides of the Atlantic. Mainstream geologists rejected his theory because he could propose no plausible mechanism for how continents could plow through solid oceanic crust. The missing mechanism was discovered through post-World War II oceanographic surveys: mid-ocean ridges where new oceanic crust is continuously generated by magma, gradually pushing older crust toward the edges of ocean basins where it is subducted back into the mantle. Once the mechanism was established, the evidence Wegener had marshaled was reinterpreted as compelling confirmation of a comprehensive theory.`,
