    id: 'act-read-100',
    passage: `Language extinction is accelerating at a rate that alarms linguists. Of the approximately 7,000 languages spoken today, roughly half are projected to fall silent by the end of this century. Many of these are spoken by communities of fewer than one thousand people, often elderly, with no written literature and few younger speakers acquiring the language. Each extinct language represents an irretrievable loss not only of a communication system but of a unique cognitive framework, ecological knowledge system, and oral literary tradition. Linguists and community activists have developed documentation programs that record and archive endangered languages — creating dictionaries, grammars, and audio recordings. However, documentation preserves the artifact, not the living community of practice. The most successful revitalization efforts, like those behind Modern Hebrew and Welsh, have combined documentation with intensive schooling, political recognition, and community investment. Linguists increasingly recognize that language revitalization is not a purely scientific problem but a political and economic one.`,
